NPCs.

NPCs are the living entities that populate a map. Animals, humans, robots, and zombies all share one engine: each one walks the map, picks targets, attacks, takes damage, and dies under a unified system driven entirely by data.
Every numerical knob that controls how a creature behaves lives in a plain text info.sif file beside its sound folder, so authoring a new creature is mostly a matter of dropping audio in the right folder and writing a small text file next to it.

Every NPC belongs to one of four categories: animals, humans, robots, or zombies.
The category determines the sound pool used for its audio, and it doubles as a target tag that other NPCs can attack or ignore.
Humans are special in one respect: they auto roll a random weapon category on spawn and use the regular weapon and shield audio so a human NPC sounds armed.

Each NPC has three behavior states baked in at runtime.
The normal state is the default.
The wounded state kicks in when the creature drops below a configured health threshold and the threat is still in wounded sight range, and in this state the creature flips its movement and walks away from the threat instead of toward it.
The healing state takes over when the creature is below the threshold but no threat is in wounded sight, and it stops moving, drops its target, and ticks its own health back up over time.
Every numeric stat can be tuned per state, so a creature can be more aggressive while wounded, weaker while healing, or anything in between.

Sound packs and info.sif files.

NPC stats live in info.sif files inside the sound pack.
The engine looks for these files in two places: the current map's local pack at data/maps/decompiled/<map>/assets/npc/<category>/<subtype>/info.sif, and the global default pack at sounds/default/npc/<category>/<subtype>/info.sif.
The map local copy wins if both exist, so a map can override a global creature's stats without affecting any other map.

Each creature has its own info.sif at npc/<category>/<subtype>/info.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the creature uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to the engine defaults baked into the npc class.

Sound paths are resolved automatically by the same get_map_sound lookup the rest of the game uses.
Drop hurt, death, taunt, step, spawn, heal, and any other expected glob into the creature's folder and the engine will pick them up.
There are no audio fields in info.sif because the audio is the folder.

Field reference.

Every field in info.sif uses the form key=value, one per line.
Numeric fields can take a single number for a constant, a colon delimited triple for state specific values, or a comma range for a randomized roll.
The triple format is normal:wounded:healing for most numeric fields, where leaving out the second or third part falls back to the first.
A few fields override this convention with their own slot meanings.
Health uses a:b:c where a is max health, b is the wounded threshold, and c is the heal amount per tick.
Chase mode uses trigger:wander, with each slot a string from a fixed enum.
Chase time uses calm:random:pause, with each slot a per-purpose timer rather than a per-state value.
Teleport time uses normal:wounded:healing like most fields, but each slot accepts the literal never to disable that state, since 0 also disables.
The comma format is min,max for a fresh random roll on each use.
Fields can mix the two: 5000,15000:1000,5000:5000,15000 gives a different range per state.

Most numeric fields also accept the tokens maxx, maxy, minx, and miny.
These resolve to the map's bounds at parse time, which lets a creature cover the entire map with horizontal sight range=maxx without baking a hard coded number into a globally shared file.

horizontal att range (triple int): How many tiles horizontally the creature has to be within of its target before it can attack. Zero means the target must be on the same tile.
vertical att range (triple int): How many tiles vertically the creature has to be within of its target before it can attack.

horizontal sight range (triple int): How far horizontally the creature can see a target. The creature only pursues a target inside this range under sight based chase modes. Setting this to maxx makes the creature aware of targets anywhere on the map.
vertical sight range (triple int): The vertical equivalent of horizontal sight range.

health (special triple): The creature's hit points. Written as a:b:c where a is the maximum starting health, b is the wounded threshold the creature drops below to enter wounded mode, and c is the amount of health restored on each tick of healing. Writing a single number leaves wounded and healing disabled. The wounded threshold is the gateway: leaving b at zero means the creature never enters wounded or healing mode no matter what other state specific values are set.
heal speed (single int): Milliseconds between heal ticks while in healing mode. Accepts a comma range like 4000,8000 for a fresh roll on parse. Only fires while the third value of health is set.

lives (triple int): How many lives the creature has. Each life refills health on death until the last one runs out.

attack (triple int): The base damage the creature deals on a successful attack. Modified at runtime by level.
defense (triple int): Damage reduction applied to incoming hits. The actual reduction is defense times three, so a defense of ten removes thirty raw damage.

fire speed (triple int): Milliseconds between attack swings. Lower values mean a faster attacker.
move speed (triple int): Milliseconds between movement ticks. Lower values mean a faster mover.

level (triple double): A multiplier on attack damage and xp drop. Level one is neutral.
xp (triple double): The xp value the creature drops when killed, multiplied by level and the player's xpmod.

attacking (bool): Whether the creature can fire at all. Setting this to false makes a creature that walks but never swings.

move_x (bool): Whether the creature is allowed to move horizontally.
move_y (bool): Whether the creature is allowed to move vertically.

drop_item (bool): Whether the creature has a chance to drop a healing or stamina item on death.

chase mode (string pair): Two parts joined with a colon as trigger:wander. The trigger part decides when the creature pursues and accepts sight, always, provoke, random, or never. Sight pursues whenever a valid target is in sight range. Always pursues regardless of sight. Provoke only pursues after the creature has been hit, and calms down after losing sight for chase time's first slot. Random flips between pursuing and not pursuing on a clock controlled by chase time's second slot. Never refuses to chase but still defends in attack range. The wander part decides what the creature does while not pursuing and accepts none, roam, or patrol. None stands still. Roam picks random destinations within move_x and move_y bounds and pauses between them for chase time's third slot. Patrol walks the corners of its move bounds in a fixed loop.
chase time (triple range): Three timer slots joined with colons as calm:random:pause, all in milliseconds. Each slot supports comma ranges for a fresh random roll. Calm controls how long a provoked creature stays angry after losing sight. Random controls how long each phase of the random trigger lasts before flipping. Pause controls how long a roaming creature stops between destinations. Slots not relevant to the chosen chase mode are ignored.

teleport time (triple range): Three timer slots joined with colons as normal:wounded:healing, all in milliseconds. Each slot supports comma ranges for a fresh random roll on each tick, like 5000,15000 for a teleport every five to fifteen seconds. Each slot also accepts the literal never to disable teleporting in that state, so teleport time=5000:never:never makes the creature teleport on the normal clock but never while wounded or healing. The destination uses the creature's patrol x range and patrol y range gated by tel x and tel y, the creature's *tel* clip plays at the new tile, and the loop sound follows along.

tel_x (bool): Whether a teleport tick is allowed to randomize the creature's x coordinate. With tel_y false this gives a horizontal only warp, matching the boss telleble flag.
tel_y (bool): Whether a teleport tick is allowed to randomize the creature's y coordinate. Combined with tel_x both true the creature can jump to any tile on the map.
With both bools false the teleport feature is off entirely, so the time field is ignored.

patrol x range (range): Minimum and maximum x tiles the creature will roam, patrol, or teleport into, written as min,max. Each value accepts the tokens minx and maxx as well as a literal number, so patrol x range=15,30 confines a guard to a thirty tile horizontal post and patrol x range=minx,maxx restores the full map sweep. Pursuit is left unbounded, so a guard can still chase the player past their post and walk back when calm.
patrol y range (range): The vertical equivalent of patrol x range, with miny and maxy as the supported tokens.
Both ranges default to the full map when absent. The roam destination picker, patrol corner picker, and teleport destination picker all read from these fields, so a single patrol box keeps a creature anchored across all three movement modes.

targets (csv list): What the creature attacks. The default is player, matching the original behavior. Other accepted values are animals, humans, robots, zombies, the shorthand all for everything, and the special value none for a fully passive creature that walks around without attacking anything. Multiple values can be combined with commas, like player,zombies for a creature that hunts you and zombies but ignores everyone else.
A creature with targets=none is also invulnerable. Bullets pass through them without dealing damage or being consumed, so a pacifist villager cannot be killed by player or npc fire, only despawned with the map.

Provoke on hit. Any creature that takes damage flips to a provoked state and starts chasing whatever attacked it, regardless of which chase trigger it was authored with. A creature with chase mode=sight that has not yet seen you will still charge after you put a bullet in it, then calm down again after losing sight for chase time's calm slot. The one exception is chase mode=never, which is the only trigger that opts out of this universal provoke override. A never creature stays put under fire, only swinging back if you walk into its attack range.

NPC builder.

Opening the NPC entry from the builder menu brings up a five button chooser that covers every authoring action: add, edit, remove, spawn, and view.
The same form reopens after each action so you can chain operations without bouncing back to the map.

Add. Picks a path, category, and subtype from three lists, then opens a flat form with every parsed info.sif field as its own input plus checkboxes for the booleans.
The path list chooses whether the file is written to the global default pack or to the current map's local pack.
The category and subtype lists are populated from the actual folders on disk under the chosen path.
Every field is required on save, with no defaults, so the saved file always has a complete entry for every key.
If an info.sif already exists for the chosen NPC the form prompts to overwrite before writing.

Edit. Same three list selection as Add, but the subtype list filters to only show creatures that already have an info.sif.
Selecting one opens the same flat form prefilled with the existing values.
Saving silently overwrites the file with no prompt because editing always intends to replace what's there.

Remove. Picks a path and a category, then offers a multi select list of configured subtypes.
Toggling subtypes with space adds them to the deletion set, and pressing remove brings up a confirmation prompt with the count of files about to be deleted.
Only the info.sif files are removed; the audio folders themselves are left untouched.

Spawn. Routes to the existing direct spawn flow, which is the same form that used to open before the chooser was added.
Asks for x, y, scale level, a path, and a category and subtype, then writes the spawn line into the map's info.sif and immediately spawns the creature.
The path list here has three options: any, global, and map. Any merges both pools into the subtype list and lets the spawned creature use the map local copy when present and the global one otherwise. Global filters the subtype list to only what's in the global pack and pins the spawn to read from there. Map filters to only what's in the map's local pack and pins the spawn to read from there. The chosen path is stored on the spawn line so each creature remembers which source to use.

View. Picks a path, category, and subtype like the others, with the subtype list filtered to configured creatures.
Below the lists is a read only multiline contents box that shows the raw info.sif text for the focused subtype.
Arrowing through the subtype list updates the contents box in real time so you can scan multiple files without reopening the form.

Spawn line format.

When the Spawn button writes a creature into a map, it appends a line to the map's info.sif at data/maps/decompiled/<map>/info.sif in the form npc x y scale path category subtype.
The six fields are space separated, where x and y are the tile coordinates the creature spawns at, scale is an integer scale level, path is one of any, global, or map, and category and subtype name the folder under sounds/<pack>/npc/.
The path value decides where the creature reads its info.sif from. Any uses the map's local copy if it exists and falls back to the global pack otherwise. Global pins the lookup to sounds/<pack>/npc/ even if a map local copy is present. Map pins it to data/maps/decompiled/<map>/assets/npc/ and refuses the global fallback. This lets two creatures of the same name on the same map intentionally read different stats by pointing at different paths.
A subtype of none places nothing and is silently ignored at parse time, which is useful as a placeholder when blocking out a map.
The line is parsed back into spawn_npc on map load, so editing this file by hand is a valid way to bulk place creatures without going through the builder.

Scale level.

The scale value on a spawn line decides whether the creature uses its hand authored stats or auto scales to the player.

A scale level of zero spawns the creature with the exact health, attack, ranges, and every other stat the info.sif file provides, which is the right choice for hand placed peaceful villagers, tutorial creatures, or set piece encounters where you want exact control.
A scale level of one or higher overrides those stats with auto generated values: attack ranges collapse to zero, sight ranges expand to the full map, max health and attack are derived from the player's current xp, lives drop to one, fire and move timers are randomized between one hundred and one thousand milliseconds, the level field is set to the chosen scale value, the xp drop equals the level, and movement and item drops are randomized booleans.

Any scale level above zero scales the spawned creature to threaten the player at their current progression, which is what bosses, turrets, and spawn zones use under the hood.
The wounded and healing variant stats are also blanked out under scale, so an auto scaled creature has no flee or healing behavior even if the underlying info.sif configures one.

NPC zones.

NPC zones are the auto respawn variant of a single spawn line.
Instead of placing one creature once, a zone defines a horizontal range and a y coordinate that, when the player walks across it, spawns a creature on a timer.
Zones live in the map info.sif as npc_zone minx maxx y spawntime scale path category subtype, written by the npc zone builder under zones.
Walking onto any tile in the zone's minx to maxx range at the matching y starts the spawn timer, and once spawntime milliseconds have elapsed a creature is spawned at a random x inside the range, the timer restarts, and the next spawn is queued.
Setting subtype to random rolls a random folder from the chosen category on every spawn, so a single zone can spit out a different creature each time it fires.
The scale field works the same as on spawn lines: zero uses static info.sif stats, one or higher auto scales to the player. The path field works the same way too, with any, global, and map deciding which info.sif copy each spawned creature reads from.
Combined with random subtype and a high scale, a zone becomes an open ended encounter generator that keeps producing fresh threats as long as you stand in it.
